snippet.textDisplay: I own a 2016 WRX base model. I think it's hard to beat it for the money, it offered the most value for the money.  I drive 90 miles a day due to my commute so I try to buy cars that offer the most for the money.  I currently have 97,000 miles on my 3 year old WRX.  I do require all wheel drive for winters in the Northwest, in the Seattle area.  The winters in the Northwest have varying condition between icey roads and snow.  I'm also a avid skier and often times the passes requires you to put on chains due to the volume of snow we get.  If you have all wheel drive this isn't required.  This is a big plus having the WRX for it's not only a big pain to chain up its dangerous putting chains on a car on a icy snowy road, you could possibly get hit by another car.  So yes having all wheel drive is totally worth it.  In closing when you combine the performance and the economy of the (28 MPG) the car it's a decent deal, only in the base trim in my opinion.   As for the car you tested I would definitely go for the base STI as opposed to a WRX in high trim level.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's a bushing problem. For the older cars, a lot of this was in the rear diff. There's a lot of twist there. Once you look at the front too, the engine and transmission also floats on soft bushings, again has a bunch of rotation. All the squish means you have a lot of driveline rubberbanding, which makes driving these cars smooth very hard. Unfortunately, you have to upgrade a bunch of bushings to fix the issue, BUT...you can fix it.


The rev hang and input delay is in part a set delay in the ECU. Even on the other drive by wire ECUs, there was a 1/3 second delay set. This could be zeroed in the ECU to reduce this issue. I don't know if newer years just got a bigger delay number. Other aspects include things like throttle mapping and how it manages torque delivery (favoring throttle plate angle vs boost targeting and spool up delay), and also includes the above bushing issue because ALL of this is delay that's happening behind the scenes you just don't feel. A lighter flywheel also improves rev behavior.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm in MN and this is my midlife crisis compromise car i'm aiming for. I'm not going to get clearance to have a separate car just for fun so I have to be able to still haul 2 kids in what I get.  Wish it still came in a hatch, but seats that tip down will have to do. 4 doors, can still drive it peppy. On the AWD vs snow tires--a fresh pair of snow tires will make any front wheel drive car take on nearly everything in the snow, but AWD can get you through an icy patch where one tire might want to spin free but the power gets sent to the rest and you're free and clear. I've got a Fit with snows and an Outback without and in normal winter they perform mostly the same. But I will say I look with envy on the Subarus I see WITH snow tires. That has to feel pure victory.

snippet.textDisplay:
Best thing about a WRX is no nannying gizmos. It's one of the last, pure, simple rally cars for the road. The rev hang out of 1st gear is a bit annoying, but everything else is fantastic.


Can't say I understand the pricing strategy for the trims, though. I bought my base 2015 WRX new for under $27K USD, and never felt anything above the base model was worth the money. $35K for the "Limited" was ridiculous and I had to hunt for a base model. I nearly had a heart attack once I started seeing Civic Type R and even the old Focus RS selling for close to $40K.
